    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right to be concerned about raw pointers in high-speed trading systems; they can lead to subtle bugs and performance penalties if not managed perfectly. Here's how you can refactor your snippet using `std::unique_ptr` to ensure automatic memory management and eliminate the need for manual `delete` calls:\n\n```cpp\n#include <memory>\n\nvoid processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order) {\n    if (order->isValid()) {\n        executeTrade(order);\n    }\n    // No need to delete; unique_ptr handles cleanup automatically\n}\n\n// Caller side\nOrder* data = /* ... */;\nstd::unique_ptr<Order> newOrder = std::make_unique<Order>(data);\nprocessOrder(std::move(newOrder));\n```\n\nBy using `std::unique_ptr`, ownership is transferred cleanly, and the destructor runs automatically when the pointer goes out of scope. This removes the risk of forgetting to `delete` and ensures the heap footprint stays under control. For even more safety, you might consider using `std::shared_ptr` if multiple components need to own the same order object, though `unique_ptr` is usually preferred for single ownership scenarios.",
      "source": "target",
